english:
  title: Record of the Relics of Shakyamuni Buddha at Tongdo Temple in Yangzhou
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the twenty-fourth day of the eighth month of the twelfth year of Hongwu, in the year of the Rooster, the Venerable Wol-song, Chief Abbot of Tongdo Temple of the Namsan School, a Buddhist monk bearing the imperial title Cittamaharaja of Perfect Understanding and Unobstructed Eloquence, came to the capital bearing sacred treasures that Tongdo Temple had guarded through the generations—treasures brought by the monk Jajang from China. These included the crown-bone of Shakyamuni Buddha, four relics, a kasaya robe adorned with gold, and several leaves of the Bodhi tree. He sought out Lee Deuk-bun, Evaluator of the Court, and spoke thus:

    "Since the year of the Rabbit, through the benevolence of the throne, I have dwelt in this temple. In the fourth month of the year of the Snake, when the Japanese raiders came seeking the relics, I buried them deep in fear of their discovery and fled, carrying them on my back. This year, on the fifteenth day of the intercalary fifth month, when the raiders returned, I again bore the relics and climbed the hillside behind the temple, concealing them among thorns and wild grasses. I heard the invaders cry out: 'Where is the abbot? Where are the relics?' They seized and tortured the temple servants seeking answers, but as darkness fell and rain continued unceasing, no pursuers followed. I crossed the mountains to Eonyang, and the next day encountered a temple servant with my horse. We wept together at our reunion. Hoping to return, yet finding the raiders had not withdrawn and the new abbot about to arrive with nowhere to lodge these treasures, I resolved to bring them here."

    When Lee, the benefactor, heard that the relics had arrived, though he lay ill with some affliction, he suddenly rose up, exclaiming: "The relics have come to my home! How blessed and fortunate!" And his sickness immediately departed.

    When he brought word of this to the palace, it happened that the empress dowager had been confined by illness for a month. The Minister of State Mok In-gil and the Counselor Hong Yeong-tong brought the matter before the throne. The Empress Dowager Gyun-bi received the news with utmost reverence, performing the rites of honor. The Empress Dowager herself presented a silver vessel and precious pearls, commanding the Inner Court Official Park Eul-saeng to enshrine them at Songnim Temple. This was done because Lee had undertaken the renovation of this temple and established a dedication ceremony.

    Throughout the realm, from the highest to the lowest, from the wise to the simple, people flocked like waves to pray for a share of these sacred relics. Lee received three; Prince Yeongchang Yoo received three; Councillor Yun Hwan received fifteen; Lady Cho, wife of the Lord of Hoeseong Hwang Sang, received more than thirty; the monks of Cheonma Mountain received three; the monks of Seongeo Mountain received four; and the Lord of Hoeseong himself received one. Wol-song, having stepped out on other duties when devotees came seeking relics, departed with his portion, knowing not all that had transpired.

    The following year, in the sixth month, Lee came to me and spoke thus: "When I was imprisoned in Gangnam and suffered the scourge, I made a vow: if I should live to return, I would visit the sacred mountains of our realm. Tongdo Temple was foremost in my heart. Upon my return, the late king sent me forth with incense, commanding that I travel to each sacred place and perform the rites. When I came to Tongdo, I received six relics. Can it be said that Lee Deuk-bun has no connection to the Buddha?"

    These relics, which have dwelt at Tongdo since the time of King Sondok of Silla, have for nearly five hundred years never once come to the capital. Now, at the beginning of our present sovereign's reign, just as we officials were taking our positions, Abbot Wol-song brought them forth. This is surely no mere chance.

    When Lee reported this to the throne, the king commanded: "Let the Director of the Hall of Worthies, the official Lee Saek, commit this account to writing." Thus I have followed Wol-song and gathered his testimony, continuing with Lee's own words, and titled this record: "A Record of the Relics of Shakyamuni Buddha at Tongdo Temple."

    Written on the twenty-first day of this month.
  footnotes:
    - Jajang (慈藏) was a renowned 7th-century Korean Buddhist monk who traveled to Tang China and brought back Buddhist scriptures and relics to Korea, greatly influencing Korean Buddhism.
    - The Empress Dowager Gyun-bi (謹妃) was the mother of King Sejong the Great, illustrating the high status and reverence given to these relics at court.
    - Tongdo Temple remains one of Korea's most important Buddhist temples and is believed to house actual relics of the Buddha, making this historical account particularly significant in Korean Buddhist tradition.
